<DOC><DOCNO> AP880624-0278 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-88 0907EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d f BC-Japan-COCOM     06-24 0143</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Japan-COCOM,0148</SECOND><HEAD>One-Month Export Ban Imposed On Company For COCOM Violation</HEAD><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A small Japanese trading company convicted ofillegally selling security-sensitive electronic equipment to Chinawill be barred from exporting its products for one month, theMinistry of International Trade and Industry said Friday.   An MITI official said the ban against the Shinsei Koeki Co.stemmed from the company's conviction Monday in a district court,and will begin July 1.   The court found Shinsei Koeki guilty of selling two sets ofelectronic measuring equipment to China between June 1985 andNovember 1986 without government permission. It fined the small,Tokyo-based trading company 200,000 yen, or about $1,550.   The high-technology equipment is among 178 strategic itemsrestricted by the government under the rules of the CoordinatingCommittee for Multilateral Export Controls, a Paris-based watchdogbody on trade with communist countries.</TEXT></DOC>